## Cross-cutting policies

<!-- PROJECT: Some concerns can't be cleanly assigned to a layer
because they cut across multiple layers.  Document each policy here:
where it lives, what calls it, what it enforces.  Skip layers that
don't apply. -->

Some concerns are vendor / integration / consumer-agnostic and live in
shared sibling modules at the package root rather than per-layer-1
implementation.  Each policy is called by multiple `<COMPONENTs>` to
keep cross-`<COMPONENT>` behaviour consistent:

**`<EXAMPLE: Hash-portability policy>`** (`<path>`).  When a render
path consumes `<sensitive field>`, it calls `<helper>` to decide
whether the target accepts that form.  Mismatches emit a comment in
the target's native syntax instead of leaking the value as plaintext.

**`<EXAMPLE: Naming-value sanitisation>`** (`<path>`).  Some target
parsers reject whitespace / unicode / shell metacharacters in
identifier tokens; renderers call `<sanitise_helper>` so the wire form
round-trips through the target's own parser.  Source state preserved
on `<CORE_ABSTRACTION>`, sanitised only at the wire boundary.

When adding a new `<COMPONENT>`, audit each policy and decide whether
to opt in.  Most cases: opt in.  Re-implementing the policy locally
is the wrong call.

