## Audit / verification harness

<!-- PROJECT: This section is THE distinguishing feature of the
matrix-honesty discipline.  If your project verifies its own claims
against an explicit expectation matrix (cross-vendor drift, schema
compliance, fuzzed property checks, golden-file regression), document
the harness here.  Skip if you don't have one yet — but consider
adding one; the discipline pays off. -->

Beyond the standard test layers (unit / integration / e2e), a
separate audit harness lives at `<tools/audit_path>`.  It runs every
`(<input dimension>, <output dimension>, fixture)` triple through the
full pipeline and classifies per-`<CORE_ABSTRACTION>`-field drift
into one of N variance classes:

* **`ALIGNED`** — drift matches expectation; no action.
* **`<COMPONENT>_BUG`** — drifted where expectation says "should
  succeed".  This is the high-severity signal — real drift the
  `<COMPONENT>` author should fix.
* **`EXPECTED_LOSSY`** — drifted, expectation says
  `disposition: lossy` (acknowledged loss).
* **`EXPECTED_UNSUPPORTED`** — drifted, expectation says
  `disposition: unsupported` (target has no equivalent).
* **`METHODOLOGY_ISSUE_under`** — expectation says lossy/unsupported
  but the cell actually aligns (over-claiming loss).
* **`METHODOLOGY_ISSUE_over`** — expectation says good but cell is
  not_applicable (over-claiming applicability).
* **`STRUCTURAL_ONLY`** — list-row count drift collapsed to a single
  signal per cell-parent rather than amplified across N per-field
  keys.
* **`TRIVIAL_EMPTY`** — both sides empty/zero on this field; the cell
  trivially aligns by absence of data.

<!-- PROJECT: The variance class set is exhaustive, not illustrative.
A new class is a real architectural commitment because every cell
must classify into exactly one.  Add a class only when you have
real-world cells that don't fit any existing class. -->

Output committed as `<results path>` so the matrix is reviewable in
git history — not just at run time.  Per-`<COMPONENT>` investigation
reports live alongside.  This audit gates "is the cross-`<COMPONENT>`
behaviour honest?" — failing `<COMPONENT>_BUG` cells become backlog
items; failing `METHODOLOGY` cells flag expectation drift.

See [`docs/templates/METHODOLOGY.md`](docs/templates/METHODOLOGY.md)
for the rationale behind the variance-class set and why `TRIVIAL_EMPTY`
matters for keeping the signal-to-noise ratio actionable.

